Reasoning: The paper discusses the expansion of RDF beyond its initial function as a metadata framework and into the domain of general-purpose data modeling, which is relevant to the sub-categories of databases (cs.DB) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also mentions the use of RDF triple-stores and the Linked Data community's specifications for linking RDF data sets, which are relevant to the sub-categories of data management (cs.DL) and software engineering (cs.SE). Finally, the paper discusses the need for a distributed RDF process infrastructure, which is relevant to the sub-category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC).
